d1f2c896-dee9-44f7-94b0-d84845c8ebbc	Thesis: A CI/CD Framework for Zero Downtime Deployment in Wi-Fi Mesh Networks	thesis	I recently completed my Master's thesis, focusing on bringing modern DevOps practices to resource-constrained Wi-Fi Mesh networks. The goal was to solve a common pain point: software updates on routers usually mean network interruptions.\n\nIn this post, Iâ€™ll walk through the architecture and the technology stack I built to achieve **Zero Downtime Deployment** on embedded Wi-Fi Access Points (APs).\n\n### The Motivation: Why do this?\n\nTraditional software updates for Wi-Fi devices are typically "monolithic". This means to fix a small bug or add a feature, the entire firmware needs to be reflashed, followed by a device reboot. This process is slow and causes service interruptions.\n\nWith embedded systems like **prplOS** now supporting containerization, we can decouple applications into microservices. My thesis proposes a standardized CI/CD framework to automate these updates without killing the internet connection.\n\n### System Architecture\n\nI designed a **Hierarchical Management Architecture** tailored for the tree-like topology of Wi-Fi Mesh networks.\n\nInstead of the cloud managing every single node directly, I used a tiered approach:\n\n1.  **Cloud Control Plane:** Managing the entry point.\n2.  **Root AP (Orchestrator):** The Root AP receives commands and acts as a local controller, broadcasting instructions to Extender APs via the internal network.\n3.  **Edge Execution:** All nodes execute the deployment in parallel.\n\n![Figure: Comprehensive Architecture and Workflow](path/to/your/image_fig_4_1.png)\n*(Figure 4.1 from thesis)*\n\n### The Tech Stack\n\nTo make this work on devices with limited RAM and Flash storage (like the Qualcomm IPQ9570 used in my experiments), I had to carefully select lightweight technologies.\n\n#### 1. "Build with Docker, Run with LXC"\n\nWhile Docker is great for development, a full Docker Engine is often too heavy for an embedded AP.\n\n* **OS:** I used **prplOS** (based on OpenWrt).\n* **Runtime:** I adopted a hybrid strategy. I used **GitHub Actions** to build OCI-compliant images using Docker. However, on the AP itself, I used the lightweight **LXC (Linux Containers)** runtime to execute them.\n* **Efficiency:** My experiments showed that 50 concurrent container instances consumed only about 400-600MB of RAM total, with each instance taking ~8-11MB.\n\n#### 2. Standardized Management: USP (TR-369)\n\nTo avoid proprietary lock-in, I utilized the **User Services Platform (USP/TR-369)** standard by the Broadband Forum.\n\n* **Communication:** I used **STOMP over WebSocket** for the Cloud-to-Root communication. This allows the AP (behind NAT) to maintain a persistent connection to the cloud.\n* **Internal Signaling:** Inside the AP, I utilized Unix Domain Sockets (UDS) for high-performance communication between the USP Agent and the deployment controller.\n\n![Figure: End-to-End Architecture](path/to/your/image_fig_4_2.png)\n*(Figure 4.2 from thesis)*\n\n#### 3. The Core Magic: Zero Downtime via iptables\n\nThis is the most critical part of the thesis. To eliminate the downtime that usually happens when restarting a container (Stop-then-Start), I implemented a **Seamless Traffic Steering** mechanism using the Linux Kernel's native **iptables**.\n\nThe process works like this:\n\n1.  **Parallel Execution:** The new version of the container (V2) is started in the background while V1 is still running.\n2.  **Shadow Chain:** The system pre-constructs a new iptables rule chain (a "Shadow Chain") in memory.\n3.  **Atomic Switch:** Once V2 is ready, I use a single atomic operation to switch the traffic flow to the new chain.\n\nThis results in **Zero Packet Loss** during the update.\n\n#### 4. Advanced Deployment Strategies\n\nBy utilizing the `statistic` module in iptables, I also implemented advanced deployment strategies:\n\n* **Blue-Green Deployment:** Instant cutover from 0% to 100% traffic.\n* **Canary Deployment:** Gradually shifting traffic (e.g., 10% -> 20% -> 100%) to the new version to minimize risk.\n\n![Figure: Sequence Diagram of Automated Deployment](path/to/your/image_fig_4_11.png)\n*(Figure 4.11 from thesis)*\n\n### Results\n\nThe evaluation results were very promising:\n\n* **Speed:** The entire End-to-End deployment takes less than **30 seconds** on average.\n* **Reliability:** Compared to a traditional restart which caused ~50-70ms of downtime and packet loss, my framework achieved **0ms downtime**.\n* **Efficiency:** The system proved to be lightweight enough for consumer-grade hardware, confirming the feasibility of running microservices on the edge.\n\nThis thesis demonstrates that we can bring carrier-grade reliability and modern DevOps agility to Wi-Fi Mesh networks without upgrading the hardware.	t	2026-01-09 00:00:00	2026-01-24 17:23:59.948	f	\N	0	Pending
72597140-e1a3-4b22-afe8-3da2d2969ccd	My Personal Website's Storage Infra: Switching MinIO to RustFS	switching-minio-to-rustfs	# From Database Bloat to Object Storage: My Journey to RustFS\n\n> A chronicle of my personal website's storage evolutionâ€”from embedding images in the database, through MinIO and SeaweedFS, to finally settling on RustFS.\n\n## The Starting Point: The Trap of "Database-Heavy" Design\n\n### The Initial Architecture\n\nInitially, my personal website was built with a monolithic storage philosophy:\n- All data was stored directly in the database.\n- Images were embedded directly into the article content (as base64 strings).\n- There was no independent media storage system.\n\n### The Problems\n\n1.  **Database Bloat**: Storing images as base64 encoded strings caused the database size to explode rapidly.\n2.  **Performance Issues**: Every time an article loaded, the database had to read massive amounts of image data.\n3.  **Maintenance Difficulties**: There was no way to manage media files independently.\n4.  **Poor Scalability**: The system could not effectively handle a large volume of images.\n\n## First Evolution: Introducing MinIO\n\n### Why MinIO?\n\nIn 2024, MinIO was the go-to open-source S3-compatible object storage solution:\n- âœ… Full S3 API compatibility.\n- âœ… Simple Docker deployment.\n- âœ… Active developer community.\n- âœ… Rich documentation.\n\n### Architectural Change\n\n```text\nBefore (DB Storage):\nUser â†’ Next.js â†’ PostgreSQL (Containing image base64 data)\n\nAfter (MinIO):\nUser â†’ Next.js â†’ PostgreSQL (Articles) + MinIO (Images)	t	2026-01-22 00:00:00	2026-01-24 17:24:16.35	f	\N	0	Pending
7e19f76d-5971-41ff-96cf-6dbebb85ae9d	242. Valid Anagram	valid-anagram	## [242. Valid Anagram](https://leetcode.com/problems/valid-anagram)\n\n### Description\nGiven two strings `s` and `t`, return `true` if `t` is an `anagram` of `s`, and `false` otherwise.\n\n**Example 1**\n```\nInput: s = "anagram", t = "nagaram"\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n```\nInput: s = "rat", t = "car"\nOutput: false\n```\n\n## 1. Hash Map Approach (Optimal)\nIf the input constraints were removed (e.g., containing symbols, uppercase letters), `unordered_map` becomes the most intuitive and robust solution.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    bool isAnagram(string s, string t) {\n        if (s.size() != t.size())\n            return false;\n\n        unordered_map<char, int> umap;\n\n        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {\n            umap[s[i]]++;\n        }\n\n        for (int j = 0; j < t.size(); j++) {\n            umap[t[j]]--;\n            \n            if (umap[t[j]] < 0) {\n                return false;\n            }\n        }\n\n        return true;\n    }\n};\n```\n\nComplexity Analysis\n- Time Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - We iterate through the string once.\n- Space Complexity: $O(1)$ / $O(k)$\n    - For English letters, map size is max 26 ($O(1)$).\n    - For general Unicode, size is proportional to unique characters ($O(k)$).	f	2026-01-24 00:00:00	2026-01-24 17:26:10.335	f	Leetcode/HashMap	0	 
97736f0d-3df1-4667-b2e1-0c1291eede09	1. Two Sum	two-sum	## [1. Two Sum](https://leetcode.com/problems/two-sum/)\n\n### Description\nGiven an array of integers `nums` and an integer `target`, return indices of the two numbers such that they add up to `target`.\n\nYou may assume that each input would have exactly one solution, and you may not use the same element twice.\n\nYou can return the answer in any order.\n\n**Example 1**\n```\nInput: nums = [2,7,11,15], target = 9\nOutput: [0,1]\nExplanation: Because nums[0] + nums[1] == 9, we return [0, 1].\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n```\nInput: nums = [3,2,4], target = 6\nOutput: [1,2]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n```\nInput: nums = [3,3], target = 6\nOutput: [0,1]\n```\n\n\n## 1. Brute Force Approach\n**Logic:** Check every possible pair of numbers using nested loops.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {\n        \n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {\n            for (int j = i + 1; j < nums.size(); j++) {\n                if (nums[i] + nums[j] == target) {\n                    return {i, j};\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        \n        return {};\n    }\n};\n```\nComplexity Analysis\n- Time Complexity: $O(n^2)$\n    - Analysis: We have two nested loops. If input size is $n$, we perform roughly $n \\times n$ operations.\n- Space Complexity: $O(1)$\n    - No extra data structures used.\n\n\n## 2. Hash Map Approach (Optimal)\nLogic: Use a Hash Map (`std::unordered_map`) to store numbers we have seen (`<Number, Index>`). For each number `x`, we check if `target - x` exists in the map. If yes, we found the pair. If no, we add `x` to the map.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {\n        // Key: number value, Value: index\n        unordered_map<int, int> umap;\n\n        // Loop runs N times -> O(N)\n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {\n            int complement = target - nums[i];\n\n            // Hash Map Lookup (count/find) takes O(1) on average\n            if (umap.count(complement) > 0) {\n                return {i, umap.at(complement)};\n            } else {\n                // Hash Map Insert takes O(1) on average\n                umap.insert({nums[i], i}); \n            }\n        }\n        return {};\n    }\n};\n```\nComplexity Analysis\n- Time Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Calculation: The loop runs $n$ times. Inside the loop, hash map operations (`lookup` and `insert`) take constant time $O(1)$ on average.\n    - Total: $n \\times O(1) = O(n)$.\n- Space Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? In the worst case (no pair found until the end), the hash map will store all $n$ elements.\n- Trade-off: We use extra space ($O(n)$ memory) to reduce time from $O(n^2)$ to $O(n)$.	f	2026-01-24 00:00:00	2026-01-24 17:25:56.963	f	Leetcode/HashMap	0	 
f6e6d36a-b468-42f8-84b3-528a7495fee1	217. Contains Duplicate	contains-duplicate	## [217. Contains Duplicate](https://leetcode.com/problems/contains-duplicate)\n\n### Description\nGiven an integer array `nums`, return `true `if any value appears at least twice in the array, and return `false `if every element is distinct.\n\n**Example 1**\n```\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,1]\nOutput: true\nExplanation:\nThe element 1 occurs at the indices 0 and 3.\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n```\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,4]\nOutput: false\nExplanation:\nAll elements are distinct.\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n```\nInput: nums = [1,1,1,3,3,4,3,2,4,2]\nOutput: true\n```\n\n## 1. Hash Map Approach (Optimal)\n**Logic:** Use a Hash Map or Hash Set to track elements we have seen. If we encounter a number that is already in the map/set, return `true`.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {\n        // Use unordered_map to count frequencies\n        // Time: O(n), Space: O(n)\n        unordered_map<int, int> umap;\n\n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {\n            // Increment count for the current number\n            umap[nums[i]]++;\n\n            // If count becomes greater than 1, it's a duplicate\n            if (umap[nums[i]] > 1) {\n                return true;\n            }\n        }\n        return false;\n    }\n};\n```\n\nComplexity Analysis\n- Time Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? We iterate through the array once. Hash map operations (`insert`, `access`) are $O(1)$ on average.\n- Space Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? In the worst case (no duplicates), we store all $n$ elements in the map.\n- Note: Using `unordered_set `is slightly more efficient in space since we don't need to store the count (Value), just the existence (Key).	f	2026-01-24 00:00:00	2026-01-24 17:26:17.029	f	Leetcode/HashMap	0	 
