8804f50e-b421-4afb-a78b-07c02d54a263	7e19f76d-5971-41ff-96cf-6dbebb85ae9d	242. Valid Anagram	valid-anagram	## [242. Valid Anagram](https://leetcode.com/problems/valid-anagram)\n\n### Description\nGiven two strings `s` and `t`, return `true` if `t` is an `anagram` of `s`, and `false` otherwise.\n\n**Example 1**\n```\nInput: s = "anagram", t = "nagaram"\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n```\nInput: s = "rat", t = "car"\nOutput: false\n```\n\n## 1. Hash Map Approach (Optimal)\nIf the input constraints were removed (e.g., containing symbols, uppercase letters), `unordered_map` becomes the most intuitive and robust solution.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    bool isAnagram(string s, string t) {\n        if (s.size() != t.size())\n            return false;\n\n        unordered_map<char, int> umap;\n\n        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {\n            umap[s[i]]++;\n        }\n\n        for (int j = 0; j < t.size(); j++) {\n            umap[t[j]]--;\n            \n            if (umap[t[j]] < 0) {\n                return false;\n            }\n        }\n\n        return true;\n    }\n};\n```\n\nComplexity Analysis\n- Time Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - We iterate through the string once.\n- Space Complexity: $O(1)$ / $O(k)$\n    - For English letters, map size is max 26 ($O(1)$).\n    - For general Unicode, size is proportional to unique characters ($O(k)$).	f	["Leetcode"]	2026-01-24 17:02:48.426	2
1f8047e7-a16c-4d78-abd8-54714aafcf82	f6e6d36a-b468-42f8-84b3-528a7495fee1	217. Contains Duplicate	contains-duplicate	## [217. Contains Duplicate](https://leetcode.com/problems/two-sum/)\n\n### Description\nGiven an integer array `nums`, return `true `if any value appears at least twice in the array, and return `false `if every element is distinct.\n\n**Example 1**\n```\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,1]\nOutput: true\nExplanation:\nThe element 1 occurs at the indices 0 and 3.\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n```\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,4]\nOutput: false\nExplanation:\nAll elements are distinct.\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n```\nInput: nums = [1,1,1,3,3,4,3,2,4,2]\nOutput: true\n```\n\n## 1. Hash Map Approach (Optimal)\n**Logic:** Use a Hash Map or Hash Set to track elements we have seen. If we encounter a number that is already in the map/set, return `true`.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {\n        // Use unordered_map to count frequencies\n        // Time: O(n), Space: O(n)\n        unordered_map<int, int> umap;\n\n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {\n            // Increment count for the current number\n            umap[nums[i]]++;\n\n            // If count becomes greater than 1, it's a duplicate\n            if (umap[nums[i]] > 1) {\n                return true;\n            }\n        }\n        return false;\n    }\n};\n```\n\nComplexity Analysis\n\n- Time Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? We iterate through the array once. Hash map operations (`insert`, `access`) are $O(1)$ on average.\n- Space Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? In the worst case (no duplicates), we store all $n$ elements in the map.\n- Note: Using `unordered_set `is slightly more efficient in space since we don't need to store the count (Value), just the existence (Key).	f	["Leetcode"]	2026-01-24 16:00:18.189	2
efdc5b57-1c39-4e4c-b528-bfa5ddc29c24	97736f0d-3df1-4667-b2e1-0c1291eede09	1. Two Sum	two-sum	## [1. Two Sum](https://leetcode.com/problems/two-sum/)\n\n### Description\nGiven an array of integers `nums` and an integer `target`, return indices of the two numbers such that they add up to `target`.\n\nYou may assume that each input would have exactly one solution, and you may not use the same element twice.\n\nYou can return the answer in any order.\n\n**Example 1**\n```\nInput: nums = [2,7,11,15], target = 9\nOutput: [0,1]\nExplanation: Because nums[0] + nums[1] == 9, we return [0, 1].\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n```\nInput: nums = [3,2,4], target = 6\nOutput: [1,2]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n```\nInput: nums = [3,3], target = 6\nOutput: [0,1]\n```\n\n\n## 1. Brute Force Approach\n**Logic:** Check every possible pair of numbers using nested loops.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {\n        \n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {\n            for (int j = i + 1; j < nums.size(); j++) {\n                if (nums[i] + nums[j] == target) {\n                    return {i, j};\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        \n        return {};\n    }\n};\n```\n\n- Time Complexity: $O(n^2)$\n    - Analysis: We have two nested loops. If input size is $n$, we perform roughly $n \\times n$ operations.\n- Space Complexity: $O(1)$\n    - No extra data structures used.\n\n\n## 2. Hash Map Approach (Optimal)\nLogic: Use a Hash Map (`std::unordered_map`) to store numbers we have seen (`<Number, Index>`). For each number `x`, we check if `target - x` exists in the map. If yes, we found the pair. If no, we add `x` to the map.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {\n        // Key: number value, Value: index\n        unordered_map<int, int> umap;\n\n        // Loop runs N times -> O(N)\n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {\n            int complement = target - nums[i];\n\n            // Hash Map Lookup (count/find) takes O(1) on average\n            if (umap.count(complement) > 0) {\n                return {i, umap.at(complement)};\n            } else {\n                // Hash Map Insert takes O(1) on average\n                umap.insert({nums[i], i}); \n            }\n        }\n        return {};\n    }\n};\n```\n\n- Time Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Calculation: The loop runs $n$ times. Inside the loop, hash map operations (`lookup` and `insert`) take constant time $O(1)$ on average.\n    - Total: $n \\times O(1) = O(n)$.\n- Space Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? In the worst case (no pair found until the end), the hash map will store all $n$ elements.\n- Trade-off: We use extra space ($O(n)$ memory) to reduce time from $O(n^2)$ to $O(n)$.	f	["Leetcode"]	2026-01-24 16:00:30.668	14
31cd9cc9-4e2e-43a7-b72d-a8601c30642f	f6e6d36a-b468-42f8-84b3-528a7495fee1	217. Contains Duplicate	contains-duplicate	## [217. Contains Duplicate](https://leetcode.com/problems/two-sum/)\n\n### Description\nGiven an integer array `nums`, return `true `if any value appears at least twice in the array, and return `false `if every element is distinct.\n\n**Example 1**\n```\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,1]\nOutput: true\nExplanation:\nThe element 1 occurs at the indices 0 and 3.\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n```\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,4]\nOutput: false\nExplanation:\nAll elements are distinct.\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n```\nInput: nums = [1,1,1,3,3,4,3,2,4,2]\nOutput: true\n```\n\n## 1. Hash Map Approach (Optimal)\n**Logic:** Use a Hash Map or Hash Set to track elements we have seen. If we encounter a number that is already in the map/set, return `true`.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {\n        // Use unordered_map to count frequencies\n        // Time: O(n), Space: O(n)\n        unordered_map<int, int> umap;\n\n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {\n            // Increment count for the current number\n            umap[nums[i]]++;\n\n            // If count becomes greater than 1, it's a duplicate\n            if (umap[nums[i]] > 1) {\n                return true;\n            }\n        }\n        return false;\n    }\n};\n```\n\nComplexity Analysis\n- Time Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? We iterate through the array once. Hash map operations (`insert`, `access`) are $O(1)$ on average.\n- Space Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? In the worst case (no duplicates), we store all $n$ elements in the map.\n- Note: Using `unordered_set `is slightly more efficient in space since we don't need to store the count (Value), just the existence (Key).	f	["Leetcode"]	2026-01-24 16:01:22.637	3
5e68a8ae-352e-4648-b606-bc9894522d43	7e19f76d-5971-41ff-96cf-6dbebb85ae9d	242. Valid Anagram	valid-anagram	## [242. Valid Anagram](https://leetcode.com/problems/valid-anagram)\n\n### Description\nGiven two strings `s` and `t`, return `true` if `t` is an `anagram` of `s`, and `false` otherwise.\n\n**Example 1**\n```\nInput: s = "anagram", t = "nagaram"\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n```\nInput: s = "rat", t = "car"\nOutput: false\n```\n\n## 1. Hash Map Approach (Optimal)\n**Logic:** Use a Hash Map or Hash Set to track elements we have seen. If we encounter a number that is already in the map/set, return `true`.\n\n```cpp\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {\n        // Use unordered_map to count frequencies\n        // Time: O(n), Space: O(n)\n        unordered_map<int, int> umap;\n\n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {\n            // Increment count for the current number\n            umap[nums[i]]++;\n\n            // If count becomes greater than 1, it's a duplicate\n            if (umap[nums[i]] > 1) {\n                return true;\n            }\n        }\n        return false;\n    }\n};\n```\n\nComplexity Analysis\n- Time Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? We iterate through the array once. Hash map operations (`insert`, `access`) are $O(1)$ on average.\n- Space Complexity: $O(n)$\n    - Why? In the worst case (no duplicates), we store all $n$ elements in the map.\n- Note: Using `unordered_set `is slightly more efficient in space since we don't need to store the count (Value), just the existence (Key).	f	["Leetcode"]	2026-01-24 16:33:56.077	1
